data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which involve `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`. These APIs work identically in modern .NET and will compile and run correctly on .NET 8 as-is.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort migration): You could replace the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` for cleaner code:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is purely a modernization convenience — your existing code will work fine on .NET 8 without any changes.
